At 07:30 AM 3/5/2003 -0800, Erik Hanson wrote:
&gt;&quot;Tung Wai Yip&quot; &lt;tungwaiyip@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;How about extracting your error handling code and testing it by itself:
&gt;
&gt;public class Foo {
&gt;   public void bar() {
&gt;     try {
&gt;       // execute my sql query
&gt;       ResultSet rs = sql.executeQuery();
&gt;       while (rs.next()) {
&gt;         String name = rs.getString(&quot;name&quot;);
&gt;         //do my processing
&gt;       }
&gt;       sql.close();
&gt;     }
&gt;     catch (SQLException e) {
&gt;       handleSQLException(e);
&gt;     }
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   void handleSQLException(e) {
&gt;     //do my smart error handling here.
&gt;   }
&gt;}
&gt;
&gt;public class FooTest extends TestCase {
&gt;   public void testBar() {
&gt;     //do whatever tests on bar you want to do
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   public void testHandleSQLException() {
&gt;     Foo f = new Foo();
&gt;     f.handleSQLException(newSQLException(...));
&gt;     //assert that the exeption was handled correctly
&gt;   }
&gt;}
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Erik Hanson

While this is not a bad idea in general (especially to avoid duplicate 
code, or to test more complex handlers), one may still want to make certain 
that the handler method was called by bar() (mostly to guard against future 
changes).

-Kathy
